Disk Forensics > [T9]: Windows Prefetch Analysis

(8) Prefetch & SuperFetch

Prefetch is a feature in Microsoft Windows that was introduced in Windows XP. It is a component of the Memory Manager that can improve the performance of the Windows boot process and reduce the time it takes for programs to start. It does this by storing the files required by an application in RAM as soon as the application is launched, reducing disk seeking and consolidating disk reads. Prefetch is available in Windows XP, 2003, Vista, 7, 8.1, and Windows 10.

Analyzing the prefetch files can provide information about the programs that were frequently run on the system. The prefetch files are stored in the "C:\Windows\Prefetch" directory, and they have a ".pf" file extension. The Nirsoft "WinPrefetchView" tool can analyze the prefetch files and extract details such as the number of times a program was executed and the files associated with the executable.
